bio:
You’re receiving this email because we’d like your assistance in testing Planorama and our panel signup process before we go live with it to over 700 participants.  Please read the email below, follow the instructions, and then reply back to this email with what you had difficulty with, what didn’t work as intended, any software bugs you encountered, etc.  Please use as much detail as possible.  It’s better to do the whole thing for a few sessions right now, and then go back and do your full selection by the normal deadline.  This is our live server, so anything you do right now, barring catastrophe, will be saved and available as part of the real program signups. 

The sooner you can do this, the better it is, as we’re hoping to open this up to all potential participants this (Thursday) evening or first thing Friday morning.

If you know how to do this on your computer, and are able to, please record your screen and voice your thoughts as you do these tasks. Our user experience expert who is acting as our user interface designer will take those videos and use them to improve the interface (maybe not immediately, but over the next several months).  If you do this, let me know, and I’ll put you in touch with her to transfer the file via Dropbox.

If you have questions, I am available via email, via the Chicon 8 Staff Slack (if you’re on staft), via twitter DM @nchanter_x and via google chat at nchanter@chicon.org

THANK YOU!

Nchanter
Head of Program for Chicon 8.

Hello Griffin Ess!

Welcome to the next phase of our program process. At this point we’re asking two major things from you:

  • Expected availability during Chicon 8. This includes: 
    • What times of day you’re available for program each day of the convention.
    • The maximum number of program items you want to do over the course of the convention.
    • The maximum number of program items you want to do each day of the convention.
    • Major items you don’t want to be scheduled against.
  • To express interest in/sign up for individual program items:
    • You’ll search for and select specific program items you’re interested in being a panelist on.
    • You’ll then give them rankings for how much you want to be on the items.
    • We also suggest you write a little bit about what you hope to contribute to each program session you select. Some items have tailored additional instructions for prospective panelists. 
  • Please note that this process has been tested using browsers running on personal computers.  We do not recommend using a tablet or smart phone.

Please get this done by Thursday, April 28th, as our staff will start the (very long) panel assignment and scheduling process later that week. Detailed instructions are below.

We are continuing to confirm panelists, and will make sure that everyone knows their acceptance status no later than June 1st, 2022. In June we will reach out to confirm participants' bios, social media accounts, and name to use in publications. In July we will be sending participants’ first draft schedules. “Final” schedules, which you can promote far and wide, will go out in August.

Please let us know if you have any questions.

Best,
Kris “Nchanter” Snyder
On behalf of the entire Chicon 8 Program Team
 

Instructions: 

  • Log into Planorama (our Program Software System) by going to https://planorama.staging.chicon.org/
    • As this is your first time logging in, you will need to reset your password by clicking on the “forgot password” link and using the email address we sent this email to.
  • Once in, click on “profile” in the left menu. There are 4 tabs in the profile:
    • General
    • Availability & Interests
    • Session Selection
    • Session Rankings
  • General Tab
    • You can update your name(s), pronouns, email address, bio, and social media from this tab.
    • If you’re not going to be attending the convention in-person, please let us know the timezone that you will be in when you attend virtually.
  • Availability & Interests
    • Fill in the maximum number of program items you would like to be on.
      • For the full convention.
      • For each individual day of the convention.
    • Select blocks of time you will be available during the convention on the availability calendar.
      • You can select multiple time blocks per day.
    • Select any of the specific cornerstone items you do not want to be scheduled against.
    • Let us know any other scheduling constraints you have in the free text box.
  • Session Selection
    • You can filter the options for one area, look through all options (over 600!) or search based on text in the title and description. 
    • Select sessions by using the slider to the right of the description. Your selections will save automatically.
    • Tags are not implemented at this time.
  • Session Rankings
    • The list of sessions you selected will display here. For each session:
      • Add a ranking 1-3. The ranking system is explained on the tab. You may leave panels unranked.
      • Indicate moderation preference for the individual items.
      • Use the text box to tell us why you are a good choice for this panel and what you would contribute.
        • Please follow the additional prompt, if present.
        • A sentence or two is often sufficient; essays are not required.
        • We have about 1000 potential panelists and about two dozen staffers engaged in panelist assignments; this step helps us learn more about you in the context of a particular session.

bio: Laurie Mann has been an active fan since 1974.  Parenthood and a busy computer job in the '80s reduced her fanac somewhat but she was active in NESFA, worked on Boskones and Noreascons and became active online. Laurie and Jim returned to Pittsburgh in early '90s, worked on Confluences and Worldcons. She edited William Tenn's nonfiction collection Dancing Naked which was nominated for a Best Nonfiction Hugo. She's worked on Program and fan history exhibits for Worldcons and contributes to Fancyclopedia.  She hopes to have spent 3 weeks in Europe in mid-2022 celebrating her 45th anniversary with Jim.

bio: I've been costuming since childhood, have a B.A. in theater/costuming, and have over 40 years of professional costuming experience as DreamStitcher Custom Costume. Been involved with several historical re-enactment groups including SCA, Viking Age Club, and have had commissions from the MN Historical Society, Science Museum of MN, Historic Fort Snelling, as well as individual clients. I've also had commercial clients including Target, Periscope advertising and others. I've done SF/Fantasy/Anime and Video Game characters, including Harry Potter and Lord of the Rings. You may see me running around this convention as Belladonna Took, Prof. McGonagall, or (my favorite) Edna Mode.
